Certainly! Here's a LaTeX code using TikZ to draw the Olympic rings:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[line width=2pt]
    % Define colors
    \definecolor{olympicBlue}{RGB}{0,129,188}
    \definecolor{olympicYellow}{RGB}{252,177,49}
    \definecolor{olympicBlack}{RGB}{0,0,0}
    \definecolor{olympicGreen}{RGB}{0,157,87}
    \definecolor{olympicRed}{RGB}{238,51,78}

    % Draw rings
    \draw[olympicBlue] (0,0) circle (1cm);
    \draw[olympicYellow] (2.2,0) circle (1cm);
    \draw[olympicBlack] (4.4,0) circle (1cm);
    \draw[olympicGreen] (1.1,-1) circle (1cm);
    \draw[olympicRed] (3.3,-1) circle (1cm);

    % Add overlaps
    \begin{scope}
        \clip (0,0) circle (1cm);
        \draw[white, line width=4pt] (2.2,0) circle (1cm);
    \end{scope}

    \begin{scope}
        \clip (4.4,0) circle (1cm);
        \draw[white, line width=4pt] (2.2,0) circle (1cm);
    \end{scope}

    \begin{scope}
        \clip (1.1,-1) circle (1cm);
        \draw[white, line width=4pt] (0,0) circle (1cm);
        \draw[white, line width=4pt] (2.2,0) circle (1cm);
    \end{scope}

    \begin{scope}
        \clip (3.3,-1) circle (1cm);
        \draw[white, line width=4pt] (2.2,0) circle (1cm);
        \draw[white, line width=4pt] (4.4,0) circle (1cm);
    \end{scope}
\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code will produce an image of the Olympic rings with the correct colors and overlaps. Here's a breakdown of what the code does:

1. It defines the document class as standalone and imports the TikZ package.
2. It defines custom colors for each Olympic ring using the official RGB values.
3. It draws each ring as a circle with the appropriate color.
4. It creates the overlapping effect by using clipping and drawing white lines over the intersections.

To compile this code, you'll need a LaTeX distribution installed on your computer (such as TeX Live or MiKTeX) and a LaTeX editor. Save the code in a .tex file and compile it to see the result.

The output will be a standalone image of the Olympic rings that you can use in other documents or export as an image file.

